WEBVTT

00:10.222 --> 00:12.489
♪

00:16.761 --> 00:19.663
(indistinct chatter)

00:21.000 --> 00:27.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

00:33.878 --> 00:35.012
Excuse me!

00:35.014 --> 00:36.580
I've gotten separated
from my daughter.

00:36.582 --> 00:37.881
There's a police kiosk
over by...

00:37.883 --> 00:39.516
Look, can you make
an announcement from here?

00:39.518 --> 00:41.352
She's only eight years old.
Her name is Claire!

00:41.354 --> 00:43.354
Sir, I'm sorry.
This is a ticket window.

00:43.356 --> 00:44.888
Please, you have to help us!

00:44.890 --> 00:46.423
We're not from here.

00:46.425 --> 00:47.458
Daddy?

00:47.460 --> 00:48.759
Claire! Claire!

00:48.761 --> 00:50.394
Daddy! Daddy!

00:50.396 --> 00:51.629
That's him. That's him.

00:51.631 --> 00:53.464
All units, all units,
suspect in sight.

00:53.466 --> 00:55.799
Repeat: We have
the suspect in sight.

00:55.801 --> 00:57.201
Grand Central,
main concourse.

00:57.203 --> 00:59.370
Repeat: main concourse.

00:59.380 --> 01:00.680
Daddy!

01:01.548 --> 01:03.349
I love you, CC!

01:03.351 --> 01:04.666
Daddy!

01:04.668 --> 01:07.553
Wait! No! Daddy!

01:07.555 --> 01:10.439
Wow. That's pretty intense.

01:10.441 --> 01:11.557
It is, Norah.

01:11.559 --> 01:13.476
Even I'm on the edge
of my seat.

01:13.478 --> 01:17.313
You know, we decided early on
with this one to just go for it.

01:17.315 --> 01:18.647
Not pull any punches,

01:18.649 --> 01:21.450
put my character through
a living hell from scene one.

01:21.452 --> 01:24.019
There's kind of a... a Hitchcock
quality to it, right?

01:24.021 --> 01:25.905
Innocent man
wrongly pursued.

01:25.907 --> 01:27.873
That's right,
and it's... it's a great ride.

01:27.875 --> 01:30.326
And, you know,
the sacrifices that he makes

01:30.328 --> 01:32.211
to get his family whole again

01:32.213 --> 01:33.612
are ones that I think

01:33.614 --> 01:35.081
an audiences can
really relate to.

01:35.083 --> 01:36.799
Now, Norah,

01:36.801 --> 01:40.920
can we please talk
about my love life already?

01:40.922 --> 01:42.088
Oh, yeah! (laughs)
(chuckling)

01:42.090 --> 01:43.889
You brought it up,
let's talk about it.

01:43.891 --> 01:45.257
Well, you were going to.
Let's talk about it,

01:45.259 --> 01:46.926
um, because it certainly gets
a lot of attention,

01:46.928 --> 01:48.010
a lot of press.
Yeah.

01:48.012 --> 01:51.397
Can I show you
how the tabloids work?

01:51.399 --> 01:52.848
Yeah, sure.

01:55.652 --> 01:57.720
I really like your show,

01:57.722 --> 02:00.272
and I think you
are fantastic on it.

02:00.274 --> 02:02.842
Thank you.

02:02.844 --> 02:04.693
We just spent a weekend
in Cabo together

02:04.695 --> 02:05.928
and you're pregnant
with my child.

02:05.930 --> 02:07.196
(laughing):
Oh, come on.

02:07.198 --> 02:09.815
Mmm, that's how it works.
99% of the time,

02:09.817 --> 02:11.901
that's exactly how they blow it
out of proportion.

02:11.903 --> 02:14.269
Then let's talk about the
one percent that is true.

02:14.271 --> 02:16.939
Well, I think that's about
all the time we have today,

02:16.941 --> 02:18.106
ladies and gentlemen. (laughs)

02:18.108 --> 02:19.375
I'll see you at the movies.

02:19.377 --> 02:22.912
<i>Accused</i> opens in theaters
on Friday.

02:22.914 --> 02:24.046
And what's next for you?

02:24.048 --> 02:27.082
Next up is called
<i>Crime of the Century.</i>

02:27.084 --> 02:28.884
It actually-- no spoilers here--

02:28.886 --> 02:31.554
but I am trailing
an NYPD detective

02:31.556 --> 02:33.005
for the next few days.

02:33.007 --> 02:34.590
Oh.
Just getting the download.

02:34.592 --> 02:36.509
All right. Russell Berke,
always a pleasure.

02:36.511 --> 02:37.843
It is, Norah. Thank you.

02:37.845 --> 02:41.363
ARBOGAST: <i>And if you, uh, flip</i>
<i>to the next page,</i>

02:41.365 --> 02:43.115
you see a graphic
that breaks down

02:43.117 --> 02:46.552
the pattern of early retirement
based on borough, precinct,

02:46.554 --> 02:47.636
length of service, rank.

02:47.638 --> 02:49.638
Dino, just a minute.

02:49.640 --> 02:52.575
I'd like to stay
with this exit poll.

02:53.493 --> 02:56.612
You have to take it
with a grain of lt.

02:56.614 --> 02:59.281
Frank, I'd caution you not
to misinterpret those metrics.

02:59.283 --> 03:01.717
I can read, Dino.
You're saying the numbers lie?

03:01.719 --> 03:05.871
No, but if you take into account
that when a retiring cop says

03:05.873 --> 03:08.174
he didn't feel a personal
connection with the PC,

03:08.176 --> 03:10.359
it's kind of like
an assembly line worker

03:10.361 --> 03:11.927
saying he didn't feel
a personal connection

03:11.929 --> 03:13.162
with the company's president.

03:13.164 --> 03:15.581
It's not expected or assumed;
it's, uh...

03:15.583 --> 03:16.599
A non issue.

03:16.601 --> 03:18.133
I am not a president.

03:18.135 --> 03:21.470
I am a New York City cop
who was asked to be the PC,

03:21.472 --> 03:24.223
but I'm one of them.
I have to be to lead them.

03:24.225 --> 03:25.691
Actually, you don't.

03:25.693 --> 03:27.309
There's no provision
in the job profile

03:27.311 --> 03:28.394
that requires a PC

03:28.396 --> 03:30.145
to have experience on the job.

03:30.147 --> 03:33.365
But I do, and I won't lose that.

03:33.367 --> 03:35.851
What are you gonna do,
throw a barbecue for 35,000?

03:35.853 --> 03:37.286
(both chuckle)

03:40.824 --> 03:42.625
Frank, with the City Council
trying to appoint

03:42.627 --> 03:43.742
an inspector general over us...

03:43.744 --> 03:45.961
Yeah, I know, it's hardly
the time for me

03:45.963 --> 03:47.463
to go all soft and fuzzy.

03:47.465 --> 03:48.998
You have their respect, Frank.

03:49.000 --> 03:50.382
That's what matters.

03:54.471 --> 03:56.505
Okay, fine, let's move on.

04:00.376 --> 04:02.228
BAEZ: You know what
I loved you in

04:02.230 --> 04:03.095
that no one else did?

04:03.097 --> 04:04.680
(chuckling): Uh...
Um...

04:04.682 --> 04:06.298
I'm sorry.
That's all right.

04:06.300 --> 04:09.385
What I meant-- it wasn't
as huge at the box office.

04:09.387 --> 04:11.153
<i>Edge of Night.</i>
Yes!

04:11.155 --> 04:15.024
It was pretty far out there,
but you were so real.

04:16.259 --> 04:17.392
Thank you.
Yeah.

04:17.394 --> 04:19.978
Seriously, Detective,
that means a lot.

04:19.981 --> 04:22.081
Hate to interrupt
the love fest, you two,

04:22.083 --> 04:23.782
but, uh, we're almost there.

04:23.784 --> 04:26.252
We're gonna be looking
for one Yoo-Hoo Clinton:

04:26.254 --> 04:29.288
male black;
18; five, six; 150.

04:29.290 --> 04:31.423
He's wanted for
questioning in a series

04:31.425 --> 04:33.042
of armed robberies
of liquor stores.

04:33.044 --> 04:34.910
You call him Yoo-Hoo
'cause he likes the drink?

04:34.912 --> 04:38.130
No. Most nicknames usually
come off of opposites.

04:38.132 --> 04:40.432
Like, a fat guy
would be "Tin""

04:40.434 --> 04:42.751
or a short guy
would be "Shaquille""

04:42.753 --> 04:44.436
Right, so then he doesn't
like Yoo-Hoo.

04:44.438 --> 04:46.522
I don't know if he
likes Yoo-Hoo or not.

04:46.524 --> 04:47.806
(laughing):
Just kidding.

04:47.808 --> 04:49.692
His name's Yousef.
I'm sure it comes from that.

04:49.694 --> 04:51.460
So how's this gonna go down?

04:51.462 --> 04:53.779
Well, you're gonna look
for my partner and I

04:53.781 --> 04:56.031
from the backseat

04:56.033 --> 04:59.118
to move in on opposite sides
of the suspect, closing in.

04:59.120 --> 05:00.986
Sort of like a pair of pliers.

05:00.988 --> 05:04.873
And... there he is.

05:10.780 --> 05:12.331
Nice 'fro, man.

05:12.333 --> 05:13.448
(laughter)

05:13.450 --> 05:14.783
(singsongy):
Yoo-Hoo!

05:14.785 --> 05:17.303
See if you can guess
which one he is.

05:18.121 --> 05:20.055
And don't leave
the car, okay?

05:30.900 --> 05:32.651
Hey.

05:50.036 --> 05:52.588
(laughter)

05:54.040 --> 05:55.007
(tires screech, horn honks)

05:55.009 --> 05:56.592
MAN:
Hey, I'm driving here!

05:57.761 --> 05:59.094
Cops!
Cops!

05:59.846 --> 06:02.564
DANNY:
Hey! Hold it!

06:02.566 --> 06:04.767
Police!

06:08.521 --> 06:10.222
(grunts)

06:10.224 --> 06:11.890
(coughing)

06:12.792 --> 06:15.527
Drop the gun! Hey! Drop it!

06:17.781 --> 06:19.448
Grab that, partner.

06:19.450 --> 06:20.399
What the hell is wrong with you?

06:20.401 --> 06:22.350
Huh? I told you to
stay in the car.

06:22.352 --> 06:24.370
(groaning) Yousef Clinton,
you're under arrest

06:24.372 --> 06:26.288
for criminal possession
of a weapon.

06:26.290 --> 06:28.040
That's just for
starters, jackass.

06:28.042 --> 06:30.042
Yo, Russell Berke?

06:31.978 --> 06:33.062
Yo, you Russell Berke!

06:33.064 --> 06:34.380
I got slammed
by Russell Berke!

06:34.382 --> 06:35.914
You drive,
I'll ride in the back.

06:35.916 --> 06:36.965
Can I ask you something?

06:36.967 --> 06:39.134
Just as funny and nice
in person.

06:39.136 --> 06:40.252
Who? Ow!

06:40.254 --> 06:41.804
Will Smith.

06:41.806 --> 06:43.538
How you know
I was gonna ask that?

06:43.540 --> 06:46.141
Hey, maybe if you're nice,
he'll get you his autograph.

06:46.143 --> 06:47.559
Maybe Denzel, too?

06:47.561 --> 06:49.912
Maybe not.

